<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Nickel</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the stock market, short sellers are=
 often people who are betting against the price of a stock. They hope the s=
tock will go down. If it goes up, they are wrong, and they lose money. If i=
t goes up a lot, they will get margin calls; they will have to put up more =
money with their brokers to collateralize their risk. If it goes up a whole=
 lot, they will have to cut their losses by buying back the stock, which wi=
ll cause the stock to go up more, which will lead more short sellers to cap=
itulate and buy back stock, etc. This is often called a =E2=80=9Cshort sque=
eze.=E2=80=9D[1] When it happens, people who bet against the stock =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0short sellers =E2=80=94=C2=A0are sad and lose money, and people wh=
o bet on the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0long owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0are happy and =
make money.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In commodities markets, s=
hort sellers are often people who=C2=A0<em>produce=C2=A0</em>the commodity.=
 If you are an oil company, your future income will depend on the future pr=
ice of oil. In order to make sensible budgeting decisions about how much to=
 spend on drilling oil,=C2=A0you might want to lock in that future price. S=
o you might sell oil futures today to guarantee you a price in a few months=
. Or you might not; you might be bullish on oil and want full unhedged expo=
sure. Or you might hedge part of your production; if you plan to produce 1 =
million barrels you might only sell 500,000 barrels of futures. Or, since y=
ou are trading oil futures anyway and have some expertise in oil markets, y=
ou might end up net short, selling more oil than you plan to produce as a b=
et that prices will go down. But most likely you are in the oil business be=
cause you are hoping to make money drilling oil, and you are in some broad =
economic sense =E2=80=9Clong oil.=E2=80=9D (You might hedge 50% or 100% or =
150% of this year=E2=80=99s production, but you won=E2=80=99t hedge 100% of=
 <em>all of your future production.</em>) If oil prices go down you will be=
 sad; you will make money on your futures contracts, but that will only par=
tly mitigate your sadness.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Conversely, if o=
il prices go up, you will be happy, because you produce oil and your oil is=
 worth more. But you will also have a mark-to-market loss on the futures yo=
u sold to=C2=A0partially hedge your oil price risk.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Or that is the general idea. There is an important difference in t=
he cash flows of these things, though. If you are an oil company and the pr=
ice of oil goes up, you will expect to make a bit more money each day that =
you sell oil. This money will not all come in at once: If you sell 10,000 b=
arrels of oil a day and oil prices go up by $10 a barrel today, then you ca=
n expect to make an extra $36.5 million this year, but you=E2=80=99ll only =
get $100,000 of it today. The expected value of your future cash flows has =
gone up, and there are ways to turn that into money,[2] but it=E2=80=99s ha=
rd to do it=C2=A0<em>fast</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the othe=
r hand if you sold 3.65 million barrels of oil futures and oil prices go up=
 by $10 a barrel today, you will get a call from your broker asking for $36=
.5 million of margin today. Futures are mark-to-market financial products, =
and when the futures price=C2=A0goes up, the short side of the futures cont=
ract has to put up money today.[3] The result is that when prices rise, you=
r business outlook gets better, but you also need a lot of cash=C2=A0<em>no=
w</em>. The bad possibility is that you might run out of cash now and be un=
able to enjoy all that future business.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Russia=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine, and subsequent sanctions and threa=
ts of future sanctions, has been bad for expected nickel supplies, which me=
ans that nickel=C2=A0<em>prices</em> have gone up a lot, which is in expect=
ation very good for nickel=C2=A0<em>producers</em>, except when it is <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26954045.260607/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDgvbG1lLXN1c3Blbm=
RzLW5pY2tlbC10cmFkaW5nLWFmdGVyLXVucHJlY2VkZW50ZWQtcHJpY2Utc3Bpa2U_Y21waWQ9Q=
kJEMDMwODIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0=
ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBe1fdc72b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">very bad for them right now</a>:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traders, miners and processors often take short =
positions on the exchange as a hedge for their physical stocks of metal. In=
 theory, any price moves in the physical stocks and the exchange position s=
hould cancel each other out. But when prices rise sharply, anyone holding a=
 short position on the exchange needs to find ever-greater sums of collater=
al to pay margin calls.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traders and brokers=
 must deposit cash and securities, known as =E2=80=9Cmargin,=E2=80=9D on a =
regular basis to cover potential losses on their positions. If the market m=
oves against those positions, they receive a =E2=80=9Cmargin call=E2=80=9D =
requesting further funds -- and if they fail to pay, they can be forced to =
close their position.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chinese entrepreneur =
Xiang Guangda -- known as =E2=80=9CBig Shot=E2=80=9D -- has for months held=
 a large short position on the LME through his company, Tsingshan Holding G=
roup Co., the world=E2=80=99s largest nickel and stainless steel producer, =
according to people familiar with the matter. In recent days, Tsingshan has=
 been under growing pressure from its brokers to meet margin calls on that =
position -- a market dynamic which has helped to drive prices ever higher, =
the people said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a se=
nse in which this is all a bit unnatural. Yes, nickel prices should go up f=
or geopolitical reasons, but arguably they should not go up=C2=A0<em>that m=
uch</em>; arguably the extent of these moves is driven by technical factors=
 (margin calls on short sellers who are =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D long) that=
, in some sense, shouldn=E2=80=99t count. I mean. You could think that. You=
 don=E2=80=99t have to; you could instead think =E2=80=9Cno, market structu=
re is part of the real world, and if prices go up because of a short squeez=
e then prices go up, that=E2=80=99s life.=E2=80=9D But some people certainl=
y think that these price moves shouldn=E2=80=99t count, either because they=
 are generically unnatural and unfair, or more specifically because they mi=
ght blow up some traders and destabilize the market.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">One=C2=A0way to reduce this sort of pressure is to suspend some o=
f the margin calls, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/26954045.260607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jItMDMtMDgvY2hpbmEtY29uc3RydWN0aW9uLWJhbmstdW5pdC1nZXRzLXJlcHJpZXZlLW9uLW1l=
dGFsLW1hcmdpbi1jYWxscz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzA4MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWV=
tYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMDgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW=
1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb3c821b5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> which happened</a=
>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A unit of China Construction=
 Bank Corp. was given additional time by the London Metal Exchange to pay h=
undreds of millions of dollars of margin calls it missed Monday amid an unp=
recedented spike in nickel prices, according to people familiar with the ma=
tter.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reprieve from the LME means that =
the unit, called CCBI Global Markets, is not formally in default, the peopl=
e said, asking not to be identified as the matter isn=E2=80=99t public.</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another, more drastic way to redu=
ce this sort of pressure is to=C2=A0<em>suspend nickel trading</em>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26954045.260607/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDgvbG1lLXN1c3BlbmR=
zLW5pY2tlbC10cmFkaW5nLWFmdGVyLXVucHJlY2VkZW50ZWQtcHJpY2Utc3Bpa2U_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDMwODIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cCe1fdc72b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> which=C2=A0also happened</a>:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The London Metal Exchange suspended trading in its =
nickel market after an unprecedented price spike left brokers struggling to=
 pay margin calls against unprofitable short positions, in a massive squeez=
e that has embroiled the largest nickel producer as well as a major Chinese=
 bank.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nickel, used in stainless stee=
l and electric-vehicle batteries, surged as much as 250% in two days to tra=
de briefly above $100,000 a ton early Tuesday. The frenzied move -- the lar=
gest-ever on the LME -- came as investors and industrial users who had sold=
 the metal scrambled to buy the contracts back after prices initially ralli=
ed on concerns about supplies from Russia.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">A third, even more drastic way to reduce this sort of pressure=
 is to=C2=A0<em>retroactively=C2=A0</em>suspend nickel trading, by cancelin=
g trades that=C2=A0<em>already happened</em>. That happened too; from <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26954045.260607/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cubG1lLmNvbS9hcGkvc2l0ZWNvcmUvTWVtYmVyTm90aWNlc1NlYXJjaEFwaS9Eb3dubG=
9hZD9pZD0xMWZmYmEyZS1iMjQxLTQ2MmQtYjQzMC03OWJlOTI3YzMwMGY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBaaa920b8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">the LME today</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">The LME have been monitoring the impact on the LME market of =
the situation in Russia and the Ukraine, as well as the recent low-stock en=
vironment observed in various LME base metals. With immediate effect, and f=
ollowing the suspension of the LME Nickel market announced in Notice 22/052=
, the LME (acting where required through the Special Committee) has determi=
ned that it is appropriate in the circumstances to take the following actio=
ns in respect of physically settled Nickel Contracts: (i) cancel all trades=
 executed on or after 00:00 UK time on 8 March 2022 in the inter-office mar=
ket and on LMEselect until further notice (Affected Contracts); and (ii) de=
fer delivery of all physically settled Nickel Contracts due for delivery on=
 9 March 2022 and any subsequent Prompt Date in relation to which delivery =
is not practicable (as determined by the LME and notified to the market) ow=
ing to a trading suspension in line with the process in this Notice.</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously that=E2=80=99s bad! You do=
n=E2=80=99t want to break trades!=C2=A0The whole point of an exchange is th=
at it is a transparent and predictable place to agree to trades. On the oth=
er hand if price moves are=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>wild, and if they are dri=
ven too much by margin calls, you=E2=80=99re going to blow up enough exchan=
ge participants to undermine predictability anyway. (If a lot of traders go=
 bankrupt, it is hard to avoid breaking trades. If some of those traders ar=
e <em>nickel producers</em>, bankrupting them due to soaring nickel prices =
is an especially bad idea: You need them to make some more nickel!)</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you shut everything down for a while, including=
 retroactively, and hope that everyone can get their financing in order to =
make for an=C2=A0orderly reopening. In theory, if the people caught in the =
short squeeze are in fact largely big nickel producers, this should work. I=
f you=E2=80=99re a nickel producer your nickel should be worth more now, an=
d probably someone will give you some money for it.[4]</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">On the other hand if you=E2=80=99re a retail investor who was t=
hree times short nickel, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/26954045.260607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjItMDMtMDgvaW52ZXN0b3JzLXdpcGVkLW91dC1hcy1uaWNoZS1sZXZlcmFnZWQtbmlja2V=
sLXByb2R1Y3Qtc2h1dHMtZG93bj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzA4MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMDgmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB75db962d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this was not=
 your week</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors in a =
niche leveraged product betting against nickel have been wiped out after th=
e metal=E2=80=99s historic surge this week.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Issuer WisdomTree Investments announced that the Nickel 3x Daily Short exc=
hange-traded commodity (ticker 3NIS), which aims to deliver three times the=
 inverse performance of the commodity, will be redeemed following =E2=80=9C=
extreme and continual=E2=80=9D movements in the metal=E2=80=99s price.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere a nickel (the U.=
S. 5-cent coin) <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26=
954045.260607/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9qcF9rb25pbmcvc3RhdHVzLzE1MDExNjc0M=
