border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> times</a> recently ab=
out the fact that big international oil companies have joint ventures in Ru=
ssia and decided pretty hastily to exit them. Here is a Wall Street Journal=
 story about =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/26954045.260607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9vaWwtY29tcGFueS1=
icC1zaGVsbC1leHhvbi1ydXNzaWEtdWtyYWluZS0xMTY0NjYyMDE0NQ/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBa5fc4832" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">How Oil Giants=E2=80=99 Bets on Russia, Years in th=
e Making, Crumbled in Days</a>.=E2=80=9D As we have discussed, it is one th=
ing to say =E2=80=9Cwe are exiting our Russia ventures=E2=80=9D and another=
 thing to figure out how to actually do that. You can=E2=80=99t exactly sel=
l the shares of these joint ventures=C2=A0on the open market, and abandonin=
g them=C2=A0essentially means selling them to Russian companies for free. C=
onceptually the right approach is something like:</p><ol style=3D"list-styl=
e-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">Promise to get rid of them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">Cross them off the list of =E2=80=9Cassets we own=E2=80=9D and mo=
ve them to a list of =E2=80=9Cassets we don=E2=80=99t want to own,*=E2=80=
=9D with a little footnote saying =E2=80=9C*but still technically own.=E2=
=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Wait a while until things a=
re more normal, or until you find an acceptable buyer.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Eventually sell them for some amount of money.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Do something with the money.</li></ol><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously that is a very schematic description. E=
ach part is complicated but here let=E2=80=99s focus on Step 2, crossing th=
em off one list and putting them on another list. That is a pretty metaphys=
ical step; here=E2=80=99s the Journal:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Lawyers, accountants and outside advisers are working to determine =
how the oil companies can restructure their Russian holdings. They are expl=
oring complex options for ring fencing them from ongoing operations=E2=80=
=94transferring the assets to separate corporate entities=E2=80=94while win=
ding them down and trying to preserve as much value as possible, some of th=
e people close to the companies said. Options include escrow accounts with =
shareholders named as beneficiaries and special-purpose entities walled off=
 from continuing businesses.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Asset sales wo=
uld be challenging, some of the people close to the companies said. One pri=
mary goal is to avoid ceding direct control to a Russian counterpart or oth=
erwise inadvertently benefiting Russia, they said.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CEscrow accounts with shareholders named as be=
neficiaries=E2=80=9D? Like, before the restructuring, BP Plc (say) would ow=
n the asset, and any value from the asset would belong to BP=E2=80=99s shar=
eholders. After the restructuring, some entity set up by BP would own the a=
sset, and any value from the asset would belong to BP=E2=80=99s shareholder=
s. But in some legal or perhaps only metaphysical sense=C2=A0<em>BP </em>wo=
uld no longer own the asset, so it could say that it was getting out of Rus=
sian oil ventures, which is the point here.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>This is all a bit uncharted and you have some options on what you want to =
accomplish with this structure. Like:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: deci=
mal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">What does =E2=80=9Cshareholders=E2=80=9D mean? Most simply, the escrow =
account would be for whoever owns the company=E2=80=99s shares at any parti=
cular time; if the company sells the asset in 2023 and realizes some procee=
ds, it will pay out those proceeds to its shareholders in 2023. But you cou=
